The actress implored international communities to take a stand for these womenâs basic freedoms. 

In Afghanistan, women are not allowed to look at men who they arenât related to by blood or marriage, their faces, and bodies must be completely covered before they leave their homes, and theyâre prohibited from going to schools, gyms, parks, or sports clubs. Konel Bread, run by a talented Tokyo-based baker, has gained significant attention on Instagram for their unique and artistic approach to bread making. From the outside, their loaves appear ordinary, but once sliced open, they reveal intricate and colorful designs. These edible illustrations range from adorable characters and animals to nature-inspired patterns, often taking inspiration from the bakerâs children's drawings.

The process involves using natural colors derived from ingredients like cocoa, beetroot, and spinach. The technique is akin to making deco-sushi, where colored dough pieces are carefully arranged within the loaf before baking, resulting in beautiful, surprise artworks inside each slice.

Which one is better? Vote below â¬ï¸ Kuronushi, a talented Japanese artist, has captivated audiences with his innovative shadow art using cardboard and glue. His creations are intricately designed dioramas that transform when light is projected onto them. Each piece starts as an unremarkable structure but reveals a detailed shadow portrait when illuminated from the perfect angle.

One of Kuronushi's impressive works features Harry Potter. Initially, the shadow art depicts a scene from the Wizarding World, such as a broom-riding Hogwarts student against a half-moon backdrop. However, as Kuronushi rotates the cardboard box, the shadow morphs into a striking portrait of Harry Potter himself.

Another notable piece showcases Captain Jack Sparrow from "Pirates of the Caribbean." Initially, the shadow appears as a sailing ship, but with a slight turn of the box, it transforms into Johnny Depp's iconic character. This duality in his artwork emphasizes the deep connection between Sparrow and his ship.

Kuronushi's shadow art requires meticulous planning and precision. He uses a negative process, carefully removing parts of the cardboard to ensure the shadows align perfectlyâ.

Artist: @kuronushi_

If you could bring back one LA restaurant from the past - which one would it be?

Pic 1: a great pic of the Wilshire Brown Derby from 1954. Built in 1936 as a bigger & better replacement for the first Brown Derby, it survived for almost 50 years before closing unceremoniously in 1980. ð¸: Huntington Archives.

Pic 2: The Source on the Sunset Strip. A mecca for the health-conscious before there were many options - The Source was owned & operated by the Source Family. If youâve never heard or them - definitely worth looking up! ð¸: Source Family Facebook page.

Pic 3: Aliceâs in Malibu - 1984. Open from 1972-1995, it was a mainstay of Malibu residents & tourists alike. ð¸: Dean Musgrove.

Pic 4: the Hollywood outpost of Pup ânâ Taco on Western - 1974. Started by Russell Wendell (the man also behind the Big Donut chain) in 1956, the business grew to about 100 locations before the brand was purchased by Taco Bell. ð¸: Roy Hankey.

Pic 5: now I know what youâre going to say - @spagobh is still with us in Beverly Hills. But there will never be anything like the original Spago. Hereâs a shot of the one & only @wolfgangpuck at Spago back in the 80s. ð¸: Larry Davis.

Pic 6: Chasenâs - 1980. Originally opened in 1936, every star dined at Chasenâs. Famously, their chili was good enough for Elizabeth Taylor to have it flown to Italy during the filming of Cleopatra. The restaurant closed in 1995 & today is @bristolfarms! ð¸: Claremont Archives.

Pic 7: a two for one here! Ah Fongâs & Greenblattâs (in its original location on the corner) - 1976. After almost 100 years in business, Greenblattâs closed just a couple of years ago. ð¸: Ed Ruscha.

Pic 8: Tiny Naylorâs on the corner of Sunset & La Brea - ca. 1950. Owned by the same man behind Biffâs, the two chains counted more than 40 locations at one point. ð¸: Bison Archives.

Pic 9: the original Hamburger Hamlet on the corner of Sunset & Hilldale - 1960. From this one spot, the chain would grow to 24 locations. ð¸: David Sutton.

Pic 10: Trader Vicâs at the @beverlyhilton (showing its original name & signage) - ca. 1955. This celebrated bit of tiki heaven lasted 62 years until closing in 2017. ð¸: Huntington Archives.

Dear Renshin Kendo Family,

Kansha.

Kansha is a Japanese word that has meaningÂ of thanks, appreciation, or gratitude. And it is also the word that describes how I feel towards everyone in our dojo.

2022Â was very special because it was full of our " first" events.
We had the first ever kendo practice at our dojo in June,
We participated in our first tournament,
We had the first year end events,
We had the first in-house grading,

And we had many more.
Just like a new born baby, everything we did was our first time.

And guess what, we did VERY VERY well.

Thanks to our members, Renshin Kendo Dojo could continue to grow.
I feel blessed for every single practice and every single one of you.
Thank you very much.

I hope everyone practicing kendo at Renshin had a wonderful year in 2022, and I wish you all a happy, fantastic, healthy and love-full year in 2023.

Sincerely,

Bill Kim
Renshin Kendo Dojo
